        <p>
            <label for="<?php echo esc_attr( $this->get_field_id( 'content' ) ); ?>"><?php _e( 'Content (HTML allowed):', 'custom-landing-page' ); ?></label>
            <textarea class="widefat" id="<?php echo esc_attr( $this->get_field_id( 'content' ) ); ?>"
                      name="<?php echo esc_attr( $this->get_field_name( 'content' ) ); ?>" rows="10"><?php echo esc_textarea( $content ); ?></textarea>
        </p>
        <?php
    }

    // Updating widget with new settings
    public function update( $new_instance, $old_instance ) {
        $instance = array();
        $instance['title'] = ( ! empty( $new_instance['title'] ) ) ? sanitize_text_field( $new_instance['title'] ) : '';
        $instance['content'] = ( ! empty( $new_instance['content'] ) ) ? wp_kses_post( $new_instance['content'] ) : '';

        return $instance;
    }
}

// Register the custom section widget
function register_custom_section_widget() {
    register_widget( 'Custom_Section_Widget' );
}
add_action( 'widgets_init', 'register_custom_section_widget' );
```

##### **Explanation of Custom Section Widget Code:**
1. **Constructor (`__construct()`)**: Defines the widget’s name, description, and ID.
2. **`widget($args, $instance)`**: Outputs the widget content on the frontend. It includes a title and an area where users can add HTML content (e.g., tables, text, images).
3. **`form($instance)`**: Provides an admin form to enter the widget’s title and content. The content field is a **textarea** that allows HTML.
4. **`update($new_instance, $old_instance)`**: Handles saving widget settings, and sanitizes inputs to prevent any harmful code.

##### **HTML Content in Widgets:**
- The `content` field allows users to add **custom HTML**, meaning they can insert tables, images, and formatted text directly.
- This makes it highly versatile and allows for each section to contain complex HTML content like:
  ```html
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Feature</th>
        <th>Details</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Speed</td>
        <td>Fast and reliable</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Price</td>
        <td>$29/month</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <img src="https://example.com/image.jpg" alt="Sample Image">
  <p>This is a description of the services provided, along with images and tables.</p>
  ```

### **3. Adding Custom Section Widgets to the Landing Page**

- **Place Widget Area in Landing Page Template (`page.php`)**:
  To use the newly registered widget area for your landing page, you need to add the widget area to your landing page template.

```php
<?php get_header(); ?>

<main class="landing-page">
  <?php if ( is_active_sidebar( 'landing-page-sections' ) ) : ?>
    <div id="landing-page-sections" class="widget-area">
      <?php dynamic_sidebar( 'landing-page-sections' ); ?>
    </div>
  <?php endif; ?>
</main>

<?php get_footer(); ?>
```

- **Adding Widgets from Admin Dashboard**:
  1. Go to **Appearance → Widgets** in the WordPress Admin.
  2. Locate the **"Landing Page Sections"** widget area.
  3. Add multiple **“Custom Section Widgets”** to this widget area.
  4. Use the **title** and **content** fields to customize each section with HTML, text, images, or even tables.

